'''Guy I de Balliol''' was a [[Picardy|Picard]] baron who was granted land in northern [[England]] in the late eleventh-century. In the 1090s, he was established in the north of England by King [[William Rufus]], as part of King William's carve-up of the forfeited [[Earl of Northumbria|earldom of Northumberland]].<ref name=Stell-Bernard>Stell, "Balliol, Bernard de".</ref>

According to historian Frank Barlow, Balliol's dynasty was one of those that "originated in the reign" and were "planted ... in the frontier areas in order to protect and advance the kingdom".<ref>Barlow, ''William Rufus'', p. 172.</ref> Geoffrey Stell said that Guy's northern territories were given "almost certainly in return for support rendered in William's campaigns on the eastern frontier of Normandy in 1091 and 1094".<ref name=Stell-Bernard/>

Guy himself originated in a frontier area, coming from [[Bailleul-en-Vimeu]] close to [[Abbeville]] on the frontier of the [[Count of Ponthieu|county of Ponthieu]] with the [[Duke of Normandy|duchy of Normandy]].<ref name=Stell-Bernard/> Guy's nephew [[Bernard I de Balliol]] succeeded to Guy's estates before 1130 × 1133, meaning that Guy had died by then.<ref name=Stell-Bernard/>

