{{Politics of the Central African Republic}}

The '''Independent Grouping for Reflection''' ({{lang-fr|Groupement Indépendant de Reflexion}}, GIR) was a [[political party]] in the [[Central African Republic]]. The GIR was led by [[François Pehoua]], a former minister in the [[Bokassa]] cabinet. Pehoua was the GIR candidate in the [[Central African Republic presidential election, 1981|1981 presidential elections]], finishing third of five candidates with 5% of the vote. GIR was generally based amongst bureaucrats and technocrats.<ref>Thomas O'Toole (1986) ''The Central African Republic: The Continent's Hidden Heart'', Westview Press</ref>

